<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-12-05T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-12-05T15:00:00-05:00" n="192" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.5045/7: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul at Cafe Haitien</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wood</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Cape
                                        Haitien</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-05T15:00:00-05:00">December 5, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 6 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Cape Haitien district quiet under martial law. All public demonstrations
                            broken up without casualties.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wood</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>